We are observing that checkpoints are occurring very frequently, which is increasing the load on the NameNode. Currently, the checkpoint threshold is set to 1 million transactions. To reduce the frequency of checkpoints and lower the operational overhead on the NameNode, we would like to increase the threshold from 1 million transactions to 2 million transactions.

When increasing heap helps

Increase heap if you see real memory pressure, like:

Heap used stays > 85–90% for long periods

Frequent Full GC

OutOfMemoryError or “allocation failure” patterns

Metadata is growing (more files/blocks/snapshots) and used heap keeps trending up

In that case, increasing heap gives more headroom and can reduce GC frequency.

When increasing heap does NOT fix it

If the main symptom is:

HeartbeatManager skipping next heartbeat scan due to excessive pause

All DataNodes stale at once

High FSNamesystem lock queue during deletes

High RPC queue time / call queue length

Then the pause is often caused by:

Stop-the-world GC pause (can happen even with plenty of free heap)

FSNamesystem lock contention (e.g., delete storm)

RPC handler starvation (heartbeats queued behind client ops)

Disk/edits sync latency (edits/journals slow)

More heap won’t stop lock contention, and bigger heap can increase worst-case GC pause unless tuned.
